    "source": "IS_2022_09_27",
    "true_answer": "tHIS stands for transinstitutional health information system, an information system of a health care network which consists of multiple health care settings (contexts). It comprises all data, information, and knowledge processing as well as the associated human or technical actors in their respective data, information, and knowledge processing roles.",
    "generated": "A **transinstitutional health information system (tHIS)** is the socio-technical information system of a **health care network** that spans across multiple health care facilities and settings. It comprises all data, information, and knowledge processing as well as the associated human and technical actors in their respective data, information, and knowledge processing roles across institutional boundaries.\n\n**Key points about tHIS:**\n\n- It supports the exchange and integration of health data and documents across different health care institutions such as hospitals, medical offices, rehabilitation centers, nursing homes, ambulatory nursing organizations, and even personal environments (e.g., patients’ homes).\n\n- The tHIS enables comprehensive, patient-centered care by providing access to a patient’s health information regardless of where the care was provided.\n\n- It typically includes components such as transinstitutional electronic health records (EHRs), master patient indexes (MPI) for unique patient identification across institutions, communication servers or integration platforms to enable interoperability, and adherence to interoperability standards (e.g., HL7 FHIR, IHE XDS).\n\n- The tHIS supports various types of integration (data, semantic, process, user interface, and context integration) to ensure smooth information flow and coordinated care across institutional boundaries.\n\n- From the technological perspective, a tHIS is composed of the institutional information systems interoperating via standardized interfaces and communication infrastructure.\n\n- From the management perspective, it is governed and managed by governmental bodies or authorities responsible for overseeing health care in a region or country, with attention to legal, organizational, and technical aspects.\n\n**In summary:**  \nA **tHIS** is an overarching health information system that links and integrates the information systems of multiple health care institutions to support seamless sharing and use of health data for patient care, administration, management, and research across institutional and regional boundaries.\n\n---\n\n**Reference from the provided context:**  \n- Sect. 2.6:  \n  “The information system of a health care network can be called a transinstitutional health information system (tHIS).”  \n- Sect. 6.9:  \n  “The network of health care in a state or region consists... The information system of a health care network is a tHIS.”  \n- Sect. 3.11.3 (CityCare Example) and Sect. 6.11 (German Medical Informatics Initiative) provide practical illustrations of tHIS architectures and functions.",
    "transformed": "Define the term \"tHIS\".",
    "question": "tHIS?"
  },
